aVPedestrians walk past a HSBC bank branch in the City of London | Daniel Leal Olivas/AFP via Getty Images UK recruiters face staffing shortages, blame Brexit: report \u2018Employers across sectors are having to work even harder to fill jobs,\u2019 recruitment agencies say.\u000a\u000aBritish businesses faced worsening staff shortages across sectors in July as European Union workers leave the U.K., according to a report published Tuesday.\u000a\u000aThe Recruitment and Employment Confederation (REC), a group representing recruitment agencies, said that while staff appointments increased at the fastest rate in over two years, staff availability continued to decline.\u000a\u000aEmployers across sectors are having to work even harder to fill jobs as vacancies rise and candidate availability shrinks, said REC Chief Executive Kevin Green.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe parts of the economy most reliant on European workers are under even more pressure as many EU workers return home,\u201d said Green. \u201cEmployers are not just struggling to hire the brightest and best, but also people to fill roles such as chefs, drivers and warehouse workers.\u201d\u000a\u000aGreen said London, in particular, is feeling the effects of Brexit. He said hiring is still growing, but at a much slower rate compared with every other region of the U.K.\u000a\u000a\u201cFinancial services, a crucial part of the London labor market, are not hiring in their usual quantity as the uncertainty caused by Brexit makes them hesitant,\u201d Green noted.\u000a\u000aIn June, British Prime Minister Theresa May presented an offer to EU citizens living in the U.K. on citizens\u2019 rights, but EU leaders said the offer was insufficient.\u000a\u000aMichel Barnier, the EU\u2019s chief Brexit negotiator, said there was a \u201cfundamental divergence\u201d between the British and EU negotiating teams on citizens\u2019 rights, and called for \u201cmore ambition, clarity and guarantees\u201d from the U.K.\u000a\u000aEU workers are still vital to the British economy, Green said. \u201cWe can\u2019t ignore the importance of our relationship with the EU to employers. If we want to keep our jobs market successful and vibrant, we must make it easier, not harder, for employers to access the people they need.\u201d
