aVRepublican Sen. Jeff Flake received 49 percent of the vote in 2012, when he was first elected to the Senate. Nerdcast Nerdcast: It\u2019s Trump\u2019s party now\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s time for Episode 66 of the Nerdcast, POLITICO\u2019s podcast on the White House and politics. Tune in each week to geek out with us as we dive deep into the political landscape and the latest numbers that matter.\u000a\u000aDatapoint: 500,000. That\u2019s the targeted reduction in green cards issued each year under new immigration legislation that President Donald Trump officially endorsed on Wednesday.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aDatapoint: 49 percent. That\u2019s the share of the vote Republican Sen. Jeff Flake got in 2012, when he was first elected to the Senate. He\u2019s up again in 2018. But he has never been a fan of Donald Trump and he has had enough, even at a moment when he needs the base.\u000a\u000aDatapoint: $8 million. That\u2019s how much money Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell\u2019s political network, chiefly the super PAC aligned with him and run by his former chief of staff, is prepared to spend in the upcoming Alabama Senate special election \u2014 an election that Republicans are virtually assured to win.\u000a\u000aAuthors:
