aVIreland's Prime Minister Leo Varadkar delivers a speech in the Great Hall at Queen's University in Belfast | Paul faith/AFP via Getty Images Ireland\u2019s Varadkar says Brexit is the \u2018challenge of our generation\u2019 Irish PM warns that all aspects of life in Northern Ireland will be affected by Brexit.\u000a\u000aIrish Prime Minister Leo Varadkar on Friday warned that all aspects of life in Northern Ireland will be affected by Brexit.\u000a\u000a\u201cI think perhaps the challenge for our generation is Brexit,\u201d Varadkar said in a speech to students at Queens University in Belfast. \u201cThe Brexit negotiations are now well under way in Brussels. And, to quote [EU Brexit coordinator] Michel Barnier, the clock is now ticking.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe prime minister said his government would work with British and EU leaders to protect peace and prosperity across Ireland. But he said people shouldn\u2019t underestimate the challenges relating to citizens\u2019 rights, the U.K.\u2019s financial settlement and issues relating to Ireland.\u000a\u000a\u201cEvery single aspect of life in Northern Ireland could be affected by the outcome \u2014 your jobs and your economy, the border, the rights of EU citizens, the rights of cross-border workers, research funding \u2026 trade, agriculture, energy, our fisheries, aviation, EU funding, tourism, public services, the list goes on.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Irish border has become one of the trickiest issues in Brexit negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt will be no surprise to anyone here that I don\u2019t want there to be an economic border on the island, nor do I want one between Ireland and Britain. And by an economic border, I\u2019m not talking about currency or variations or tax rates. I am talking about a barrier to free trade and commerce.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe also had called for a U.K./EU customs union after Brexit, saying: \u201cIf the U.K. doesn\u2019t want to stay in the customs union perhaps there can be an EU/U.K. customs union instead. After all, we have one with Turkey. Surely we can have one with the United Kingdom?\u000a\u000a\u201cIf the U.K. does not want to stay in the single market perhaps it could enter into a deep free-trade agreement with the EU and rejoin EFTA \u2013 of which it was a member prior to accession \u2014 or the European Economic Area. If these things cannot be agreed now, perhaps we can have a long transition period during which the U.K. stays in the single market and the customs union while we work these things out.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Irish prime minister earlier this week said he hopes Brexit doesn\u2019t happen, which prompted Democratic Unionist Party leader Arlene Foster to accuse Varadkar of \u201cdisrespecting\u201d the Brexit vote.\u000a\u000aVaradkar said the tragedy of the Brexit debate was falling trust in the European project. He added that he \u201cpassionately believes\u201d being European is an essential part of modern Irish identity. In a recent Eurobarometer survey, Irish people were the most optimistic about the future of the EU.\u000a\u000aHe also said it would be \u201can enormous tragedy\u201d if Northern Ireland and the United Kingdom were cut off from the Erasmus student exchange program.
