aVFinance reform fueled by pre-Enron scandals\u000a\u000aBut Enron stood on the shoulders of presidential pardons issued to the politically connected, Buddhist temple fundraisers, the selling of the Lincoln Bedroom, the failed presidential campaigns of Ross Perot in 1992 and Sen. John McCain in 2000, and the generally accepted belief that money is a corrupting influence in politics.\u000a\u000aWASHINGTON \u2014 The easy answer, and the incomplete one, to explain the passage of campaign finance reform early Thursday is that the Enron scandal so shook members of the House of Representatives that they finally were compelled to do the previously unthinkable: vote against their political self-interest.\u000a\u000aThat collective weight finally overcame one of the capital's most durable forces, the status quo, to substantially change the way money and politics intersect in federal elections.\u000a\u000aBefore the House vote, campaign finance had been an issue of undeniable popularity with voters but also one that seemed distant and not very important to them. Therefore, politicians could claim to be for reform while taking comfort in the fact that it would never happen and that their campaigns could continue to benefit from the system they righteously decried.\u000a\u000aThere are a few exceptions, such as Sen. Russ Feingold (D-Wis.), the less-famous half of the McCain-Feingold duo that pushed campaign finance legislation through the Senate last spring.\u000a\u000a"I have a seven-year perspective on it," Feingold said. "If the real history of this is written, this was inevitable. It was built brick by brick. People will say it was Enron, but it was the combination of all the scandals that occurred as we were trying to pass the bill. . . . But it sure as heck didn't hurt to have this symbol of corporate irresponsibility."\u000a\u000aIt is possible that any celebration over the House vote is premature. If the Senate cannot agree to accept the House version of the bill, it will be sent to a House-Senate conference committee, where the long knives behind closed doors would no doubt try to gut it.\u000a\u000aA ban on soft money\u000a\u000aThe legislation bans soft money, the unlimited, largely unregulated contributions made to political parties by corporations, individuals and labor unions. In past campaigns, parties have used that money to launch scores of thinly disguised attack ads, circumventing fundraising restrictions on individual candidates. Indeed, soft money had been the donation of choice for the well-connected, with parties taking in nearly $495 million in soft money in 2000.\u000a\u000aFor his part, President Bush has signaled a willingness to sign the legislation, but he has stopped short of an endorsement. During the presidential campaign, Bush opposed the legislation even as his opponent, Democrat Al Gore, said he would make it the first proposal he sent to Capitol Hill. During his campaign, Bush raised so much money he declined to take federal matching funds.\u000a\u000aStill, opposing the bill is hardly worth the risk for the president. "Our president is not going to expend any major amount of political capital to beat this," said Curtis Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate.\u000a\u000aGans said that while Enron might have helped propel the bill to the House floor for a vote, it remains ambiguous as to whether the company's ample political donations were an apt example of what was wrong with campaign finance.\u000a\u000a"In a rational world, [Enron] probably should have done nothing about campaign finance legislation because this was a corporate fraud not condoned by the administration or either house of Congress," he said. "There seems to be no real relationship at this point between money given or lobbying and final result. But I think the aura of scandal probably helped to make this possible."
