aVAfter nearly a year of disappointment, triumphalism, hand-wringing, head-scratching and confusion, Brexit talks are finally underway. The two teams met on schedule Monday with an exchange of gifts and an agreement on how the talks would proceed. The U.K. made a significant concession by agreeing to talk about what the EU wants to talk about (the terms of the divorce) before moving on to what it wants to talk about (trade and the future relationship between the two sides).\u000a\u000aOne key issue that must be tackled early on is settling the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations to the rest of the bloc \u2014 the so-called Brexit bill. That impacts on everything else because unless the EU27 deems \u201csufficient progress\u201d has been made in the money negotiations, they say they aren\u2019t willing to move on to other things. Here\u2019s POLITICO\u2019s guide to what is at stake in 16 different policy areas once that\u2019s out of the way.\u000a\u000aTRADE\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? The U.K. and EU27 economies are interlinked to the closest possible degree, and any disruption in trade in goods or services will hit companies, banks and consumers on both sides hard \u2014 particularly the British. Hammering out a good trade deal will be difficult though \u2014 politically and in terms of time and negotiations constraints \u2014 and there\u2019s also trouble ahead at the World Trade Organization.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? EU trade deals with third countries will be affected but will continue regardless of the Brexit outcome.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: British business and consumers; German and Japanese carmakers.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: EU businesses that snap up British counterparts (e.g. airlines, banks); EU hubs like Brussels, Frankfurt, Paris (as British businesses relocate).\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether a softer Brexit preserves single market access (like Norway) or an interim deal is struck, buying time for more talks on a full trade deal.\u000a\u000aKey people on U.K. side: Philip Rycroft, second permanent secretary at the Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU), Catherine Webb, director of market access and budget at DExEU and Simon Case, director general for the U.K.-EU partnership at the U.K. Representation to the EU (UKRep).\u000a\u000aKey people on EU side: Deputy chief negotiator Sabine Weyand, Antonio Fernandez-Martos (head of international agreements, trade and customs in the EU\u2019s Brexit team).\u000a\u000aCUSTOMS/SURFACE TRANSPORT\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? The U.K.\u2019s biggest freight port and carmakers like Nissan, Toyota and BMW have issued stark warnings that leaving the EU customs union will put their businesses at risk. For the port of Dover, any border checks for truck transit would clog up roads almost immediately. Carmakers say they need access to EU markets for the output from plants in Brexit-voting areas of England like Sunderland and Derby, and they have called for interim single market and customs union access beyond 2019.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? The U.K.\u2019s rail and road systems will likely operate as normal, although London will have to figure out whether or not to follow EU policy on things like road tolling and social rules for road transporters in the medium-term.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: Car manufacturers worried about their supply chains and factory workers in their plants. Spare a thought for Ireland too \u2014 without easy access for road freight to and from the Continent via the U.K., the Emerald Isle\u2019s trade will suffer.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Everyone loses if traffic through Dover is disrupted as alternatives are slower and more expensive. But BMW has hinted it might shift production of the iconic Mini from a site near Oxford to one in the Netherlands.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. strikes a deal for tariff-free, and crucially check-free, access to the EU customs union \u2014 commonly described in London as \u201cfrictionless\u201d trade.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Philip Rycroft and Catherine Webb. Oliver Robbins, the prime minister\u2019s EU adviser who has been assigned to the thorny issue of an Irish border, assisted by Simon Case.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Antonio Fernandez-Martos. Sabine Weyand will be Robbins\u2019 counterpart on the Irish border.\u000a\u000aCITIZENS\u2019 RIGHTS\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Roughly 4.2 million EU citizens on either side of the Channel will be affected by Brexit \u2014 from British pensioners living in southern Spain to health professionals in the U.K.\u2019s National Health Service. The EU has made a priority of settling rights for citizens like pensions and the protection of \u201clife choices\u201d after March 2019. Life choices implies the rights to residence, to work and to enjoy equal treatment with nationals when it comes to employment access, working conditions, benefits and taxes.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? If the U.K. is genuine about its \u201cgenerous offer\u201d on citizens\u2019 rights, Brussels won\u2019t try to prevent the U.K. from cutting immigration after Brexit.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: The U.K.\u2019s National Health Service, British universities and London\u2019s banking sector.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: EU citizens on both sides of the Channel worried about their future status.\u000a\u000aKey decision: How will rights be enforced and protected? A role for the European Court of Justice (ECJ) is Brussels\u2019 preference and is enshrined in EU law, but that would be contrary to the \u201ctake back control\u201d desired by the U.K.\u2019s Hard Brexiteers.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Glyn Williams, director general at the Home Office.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Marie Simonsen, who is in charge of free movement of citizens and employment on Barnier\u2019s Brexit task force. Her boss is François Arbault, who is responsible for internal market and sectoral policies, but Michel Barnier, the EU\u2019s chief negotiator, will also follow this strand of the negotiations very closely.\u000a\u000aDEFENSE\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake: The EU will lose a country with a permanent seat on the U.N. Security Council, a nuclear deterrent and an army that can be deployed around the world. On the plus side, the bloc will be free to pursue defense integration \u2014 something London has always opposed. The U.K. will want to ensure it can maintain leverage in areas like the Balkans and coordinate with EU partners outside of NATO operations.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not: The EU is unlikely to create a unified army with a Pentagon-style headquarters. At least not in the short term.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: U.K. defense companies like BAE Systems if they cannot maintain access to the new EU fund for defense research; EU defense if it loses British military and technical expertise.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: The French, who currently steer EU foreign policy and will now dominate defense policy too; those in the EU who want defense integration.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether \u201cthird countries\u201d \u2014 as the U.K. will be post Brexit \u2014 will have access to EU funds and military operations.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Mark Sedwill, national security adviser to the prime minister.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Nina Obermaier, responsible for external relations and foreign and security policy on the Brexit task force.\u000a\u000aCRIME/TERRORISM/SECURITY\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Information sharing will be the key issue in negotiations on security. The U.K. is among the top four contributors to Europol\u2019s main database on crime and the fifth largest user of the agency\u2019s platform to exchange information. Britain will almost certainly lose access to both databases, which would leave EU and U.K. citizens less safe as a result.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Intelligence cooperation mainly occurs at a bilateral level, meaning that the U.K.\u2019s intelligence services will continue to partner with EU allies.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: Europol; U.K. police and citizens.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Organized criminals and terrorists operating out of the U.K.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. can obtain access to Europol\u2019s databases and the Schengen Information System \u2014 something that would require ECJ oversight.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Mark Sedwill and Chris Jones, director general at DExEU.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Nina Obermaier.\u000a\u000aDIGITAL ECONOMY\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? If London wants to keep its top reputation for startups and data innovation, it will have to negotiate ways to transfer data smoothly to and from the EU. The country\u2019s invasive surveillance practices could stand in the way of that. Migration is also high on the agenda for techies, who fear a brain drain of coders and entrepreneurs. The EU, on the other hand, stands to lose a tech-savvy member with the skills and pro-business agenda the Commission likes.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? The digital economy \u2014 everyone loves the digital economy.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: Startups in London; research departments across Europe.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Privacy advocates; EU countries that take up Britain\u2019s lead role on tech.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether a data transfer deal is struck.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Gila Sacks, director for digital and tech policy at the U.K.\u2019s department of culture, media and sports, will support the DExEU team with expertise.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: François Arbault, key person in charge of internal market and sectoral policies.\u000a\u000aAVIATION\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Some 50 percent of U.K. passenger travel is to or from the EU, and Brexit will also impact trips between the U.K. and trading partners with an open skies agreement with the EU, like the U.S. In total, 42 of the U.K.\u2019s air services agreements are through its membership of the EU and will have to be renegotiated.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Heathrow airport believes it will benefit from Brexit, provided the U.K. puts a system in place allowing for swift entry of passengers and goods.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: U.K. airlines \u2014 such as Thomas Cook, EasyJet and jet2.com \u2014 which run a lot of flights to or within EU countries; Passengers, who are likely to pay more due to reduced competition; Ireland, because it has more air traffic to the U.K. than any other EU country.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Some national airlines like Lufthansa, Air France and Alitalia are looking forward to less competition from U.K. budget airlines.\u000a\u000aKey decision: If a new air services agreement is in place by the time the U.K. leaves the EU and the single aviation market.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Peter Sorensen, who is responsible for aviation, and François Arbault, head of internal market in goods and non-financial services in the Commission\u2019s Brexit task force.\u000a\u000aCLIMATE\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? The EU has benefited from the U.K.\u2019s participation in its efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and boost renewables and energy efficiency. Britain is one of the EU\u2019s biggest emissions-cutters and a heavyweight country in favor of toughening climate policies such as the Emissions Trading System.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? The U.K.\u2019s national Climate Change Act, which aims to reduce emissions by 80 percent by 2050, is unlikely to be affected. Nor are its policies pricing emissions from power plants and phasing out coal-fired electricity by 2025.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: The EU27, which will have to divvy up the U.K.\u2019s national emissions reduction responsibilities, and the U.K., which will lose its influence as a larger member of a big bloc in international climate negotiations.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: EU27 countries that resist tougher future emissions cuts.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. pulls out of the Emissions Trading System, and whether it will continue to participate in the bloc\u2019s emission reduction efforts.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Tadhg O\u2019Briain, responsible for energy and climate and environment in the Commission\u2019s Brexit task force and Nicola Pesaresi, who is in charge of regulatory issues on subjects like climate change and financial stability that could be impacted by the U.K.\u2019s departure.\u000a\u000aENVIRONMENT\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? After Brexit, London will be free to decide whether to keep in place environmental rules and standards set by the EU over the years. If the U.K. lowers air quality standards, the EU could be directly impacted, as dirty air doesn\u2019t respect national borders. MEPs have also warned that products imported from the U.K. could, in the future, be made to lower environmental standards, undercutting EU goods.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? The U.K., home to a strong tradition of environmental activism, is unlikely to overturn environmental rules en masse, even if it does eliminate regulations it deems unuseful and uncompetitive.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: Animal and plant species protected under the EU\u2019s Habitats Directive, deemed \u201cEU red tape\u201d by British Brexiteers; the U.K. environment.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: British housing developers \u2014 who may no longer have to worry about great crested newts.\u000a\u000aKey decision: How environmental standards will be embedded in a future trade deal between the U.K. and EU countries.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Tadhg O\u2019Briain and Nicola Pesaresi.\u000a\u000aENERGY\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? New tariffs or other trade barriers could push up the price of gas and power supplies, putting the U.K., Ireland and others at risk of shortages. In another blow to Britain, they could get in the way of new investment, equipment and expertise for energy infrastructure (particularly nuclear plants).\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? The continued flow of electricity and gas between the two sides. Costs and volumes may change, planned new links might run into complications, but existing interconnectors will not disappear after Brexit.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: The Irish-Northern Irish single electricity market; U.K. energy companies in the EU; EU energy companies in Britain; the British nuclear safeguarding regime; new nuclear energy developers in the U.K.; British energy bill payers.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Not many. Maybe a few small local energy companies, like those developing shale gas, that would benefit from less international competition.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. leaves the EU\u2019s internal energy market, and whether it continues to follow a complex set of power and gas network rules that make it easier to trade between EU markets.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Tadhg O\u2019Briain and Nicola Pesaresi.\u000a\u000aFISHING\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Access is the key word in fisheries negotiations. Thousands of EU fishermen rely on U.K. waters for their daily catch. However, the EU is the largest buyer of British fish. This co-dependency means Prime Minister Theresa May\u2019s promise to wrangle back control of British seas will be difficult to keep.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? British waters are unlikely to become the Wild West of fishing because the U.K. ratified the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Seas.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: British fish processors and exporters; EU fishermen.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: U.K. fishermen; EU fish processors.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether there will be a deal brokered to swap fishing rights in British waters for access to the world\u2019s largest fish market: the EU.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Bence Tóth, responsible for agriculture, fisheries and maritime policy on Barnier\u2019s task force.\u000a\u000aHEALTH\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Brits and Europeans could lose their health insurance for emergency care when policyholders travel abroad. The way medicines will be approved in the U.K. could also be affected once it leaves the bloc. Britain also risks shortages of doctors and nurses, as those from the EU will either leave the U.K. or no longer work in its National Health Service.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Big British pharmaceutical companies will continue to do business in the EU, even if they will probably have to rely more on their continental subsidiaries inside the bloc.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: Holidaymakers, patients and the U.K.\u2019s National Health Service.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Insurance companies providing travel insurance; the EU country that gets the European Medicines Agency once it\u2019s relocated from the U.K.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. keeps the British medicines approval process aligned with that of the EU; and whether it remains in the European Health Insurance Card scheme, which provides the right to free emergency medical care in the EU.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Stefan Fuehring, who\u2019s responsible for health and food safety, as well as justice and home affairs on Barnier\u2019s task force.\u000a\u000aUNIVERSITIES\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Brexit could lead to a decline in the number of EU students coming to study in the U.K. because they would be recruited as international students, meaning their fees would rise significantly. British universities also risk losing the roughly 15 percent of their budget they get from the EU in research funding. Academics are likely to find it harder to collaborate on research projects with colleagues on the Continent. A change in visa arrangements for other European countries might also prevent them from joining British universities.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Demand for higher education is so high that even if fewer EU students came to study in Britain, universities would be no worse off financially as they compensate by taking more domestic students.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: EU students, and foreign staff and academics; the European Commission\u2019s Erasmus student-exchange program.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: British students (who will have better chances of getting a place at university); U.K. universities (that can raise tuition fees for EU nationals and so increase budgets).\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether a deal is struck giving EU students and academics access to U.K. universities and vice versa.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aFINANCIAL SERVICES\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Hundreds of international firms do business across the EU from their London headquarters thanks to so-called passports. The industry is most worried about losing its ability to operate across the bloc from British headquarters. Another issue topping the agenda is the possibility that London will lose euro-clearing activities, a nearly \u20ac1 trillion-a-day business that supports 83,000 jobs in the City of London.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? London\u2019s role as a world-class financial center. Some firms will move some of their operations, but the bulk is likely to stay, allowing the City of London and Canary Wharf to remain major international financial hubs.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: British clearing houses; the European Banking Authority; young EU talent.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Frankfurt, lawyers and banks (because they always win).\u000a\u000aKey decision: The shape and form of mutual market access, assuming the U.K. loses full single market access and passporting rights.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: Mark Bowman, director general, international finance at the Treasury and Philip Rycroft.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aAGRICULTURE\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Market access will dominate discussions, with British farmers currently hooked into sophisticated supply chains that deliver produce across Europe. Many EU farmers depend on the U.K. market, but Britain has more to lose. Restricted trade either way will deal EU farmers a heavier blow than Russia\u2019s food import ban, which devastated the industry.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Farms run razor-thin profit margins \u2014 everything is at stake.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: British farmers; Dutch and Spanish food exporters; Ireland\u2019s economy.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: There are few, but French farmers might benefit if their government \u2014 which the U.K. has traditionally hindered in agricultural affairs \u2014 pushes for a better-funded Common Agricultural Policy.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether negotiators will agree to tariff-free mutual market access.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one on the negotiating team has been specifically assigned this brief but Catherine Webb will deal with market access issues.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: Bence Tóth.\u000a\u000aSPACE\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s at stake? Whether the U.K. continues to contribute to the EU\u2019s space program will dictate whether it keeps access to contracts for satellite systems like Galileo, Europe\u2019s version of America\u2019s GPS network. The EU could also freeze British astronauts out of future space missions. As talks get underway on the broader Brexit deal, the government has set out a proposed new law allowing spaceports and satellite launches to take place in the U.K.\u000a\u000aWhat\u2019s not? Galileo will be completed whether the U.K. keeps on paying or not \u2014 some 20 of the satellites are already in orbit.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential losers: The U.K.\u2019s aerospace research institutions and NewSpace startups that have already been advised to start looking at options on the Continent.\u000a\u000aBiggest potential winners: Engineering companies and startups across the bloc, who will be quick to fill the gap left behind if the U.K. falls out of the EU\u2019s orbit.\u000a\u000aKey decision: Whether the U.K. keeps funding European space programs and contributing to broader EU research pools.\u000a\u000aKey person on U.K. side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKey person on Brussels side: No one specific on the negotiating team.\u000a\u000aKait Bolongaro, Jacopo Barigazzi, Carmen Paun, Emmet Livingstone, Hans Joachim Von Der Burchard, Joshua Posaner, Cathy Buyck, Silvia Sciorilli Borrelli, Laurens Cerulus, Giulia Paravicini, Quentin Ariès, Sara Stefanini, Kalina Oroschakoff, Marion Solletty and Cynthia Kroet contributed reporting.
