aVBrazilian superstar Neymar with PSG President Nasser Al-Khelaifi at the Parc des Princes stadium | Lionel Bonaventure/AFP via Getty Images Footballers demand EU probe into Neymar transfer \u2018Football is ever more the domain of a select group of rich, mostly European-based clubs,\u2019 says head of players\u2019 union FIFpro.\u000a\u000aA major footballers\u2019 union called on European competition regulators to examine transfer rules after the \u201cmadness\u201d of Brazilian star Neymar\u2019s \u20ac222 million move to Paris Saint-Germain.\u000a\u000a\u201cFootball is ever more the domain of a select group of rich, mostly European-based clubs,\u201d said Theo van Seggelen, the general-secretary of FIFPro \u2014 the International Federation of Professional Footballers \u2014 adding that these clubs had distorted the sport and \u201cdestroyed\u201d the level playing field.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe transfer rules governed by FIFA [world football\u2019s governing body] are anti-competitive, unjustified and illegal,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aPSG on Friday unveiled its new signing after meeting the enormous buy-out clause in Neymar\u2019s contract with FC Barcelona.\u000a\u000aNeymar\u2019s transfer also prompted antitrust allegations from the president of the Spanish league, La Liga, though on different grounds: Javier Tebas says UEFA \u2014 European football\u2019s governing body \u2014 may be abusing its monopoly over the sport in Europe by failing to enforce club spending limits evenly. UEFA said it would review PSG\u2019s compliance with the rules.\u000a\u000aFIFPro filed a competition complaint to the EU about the transfer system in 2015.\u000a\u000aAt the heart of that complaint was a 2001 Brussels decision granting an exemption from EU law for the transfer rules of FIFA. Those laws would in any other profession break free movement and competition rules. As a result, footballers do not enjoy the same employment rights as other EU citizens.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt is time the rule of law prevails over the interests of cartels,\u201d said FIFPro President Philippe Piat in 2015. \u201cThe European Commission holds the key to reforming the professional football industry more than any internal governance reform process can, by simply applying the law,\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Commission has yet to decide whether to reject or pursue the complaint. In the meantime, several senior football officials have indicated they are considering changes to reduce disparities and imbalances in the sport.
