aVBritish Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union David Davis and European Union Chief Negotiator in charge of Brexit Michel Barnier | Thierry Charlier/AFP via Getty Images Both sides want to speed up Brexit talks by meeting more frequently There are fears that there will not be \u2018sufficient progress\u2019 on exit issues by the EU\u2019s October deadline.\u000a\u000aThe U.K. and EU\u2019s chief Brexit negotiators David Davis and Michel Barnier both want to quicken the pace of Brexit negotiations by holding more frequent talks over the summer and fall, according to individuals familiar with the position in both camps.\u000a\u000aBarnier, the European Commission\u2019s chief Brexit negotiator, told a meeting of Brussels diplomats Wednesday that the chances of the talks progressing to the next stage by October were diminishing and that negotiations would have to \u201cintensify\u201d if enough progress is to be made, according to an EU diplomat present at the meeting. But he said the EU side would only be prepared to speed up if the U.K. brought substantial proposals on its financial settlement with the bloc.\u000a\u000a\u201cBarnier told us that he would be ready to organize a meeting on August 15th if it was necessary [two weeks earlier than currently planned],\u201d another EU ambassador said. \u201cIt all depends on how prepared the U.K side is.\u201d The ambassador said he doubted the talks would have progressed enough before October for them to move onto issues around the U.K.\u2019s future relationship with the EU.\u000a\u000aThe British are also pushing for an acceleration of the negotiations. According to an individual with high-level knowledge of the talks, U.K. Brexit Secretary David Davis has already told Barnier that the two sides should be meeting more frequently than the scheduled monthly talks, held within four-week cycles.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe British have been telling the EU side that one meeting a month is not enough,\u201d the individual said. \u201cDavid Davis has consistently told Barnier that we should be meeting more frequently.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe moves to push the talks forward more quickly reflect rising anxiety at the highest levels on both sides over the shrinking window to get a deal by March 2019 and also the lack of a clear path forward on many issues.\u000a\u000aThe EU side\u2019s disappointment with the limited progress made in last week\u2019s first full round of talks has heightened the sense of urgency in Brussels. Barnier intends to report back to the European Council on the progress of Brexit talks in October. The Council will then take a decision, at their summit on October 19 and 20, on whether \u201csufficient progress\u201d has been made to allow the talks to develop from focusing solely on exit issues like the U.K.\u2019s so-called Brexit bill to future relationship issues like trade and customs arrangements.\u000a\u000aThe EU diplomat, who participated in Barnier\u2019s briefing to Brussels diplomats on Wednesday, said: \u201cBarnier told diplomats that if we want to move on, we will have to intensify the pace of negotiations.\u201d The diplomat added that for talks to speed up, the British side would have to present a clearer position on a range of issues. EU negotiators were disappointed last week that the U.K. had made no proposal of a sum, or a methodology for reaching a sum, of the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations to the EU on Brexit.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe Brits must show up with a clear plan,\u201d if they wanted to speed up the talks process, the diplomat added.\u000a\u000aAt the briefing, Barnier said that if there was no progress on the Brexit bill by October he would inform the Council and that it would be \u201cout of question to talk about any future relationship,\u201d the diplomat added. Barnier told the group twice that the British did not \u201cseem to bear the consequences of their choice\u201d to leave the EU, the diplomat said.\u000a\u000aA U.K. government official said Davis \u201chas always been clear that we are committed to working hard and at pace and constructively to advance these talks as swiftly as possible \u2026 We will continue to be extremely well prepared for each round of talks.\u201d\u000a\u000aA spokesman for the U.K.\u2019s Department for Exiting the EU said: \u201cNegotiations to leave the EU are underway and we have already made good progress on a number of issues. As the secretary of state said, it is important that both sides demonstrate a dynamic and flexible approach to these negotiations.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cGovernment officials are working at pace and we are confident we will have made sufficient progress by October to advance the talks to the next phase. On the financial settlement, we have been clear that we recognize the U.K. has obligations to the EU and that the EU also has obligations to the U.K.\u201d
