aVPARIS \u2014 Here\u2019s a message from the City of Light: Don\u2019t believe the hype about Frankfurt sweeping up all of Brexit\u2019s finance jobs.\u000a\u000aWith 20 banks already signed up to move staff to Frankfurt, the city is widely considered way ahead of Paris, Amsterdam, Dublin and other cities vying to attract the finance sector that will be leaving London due to Brexit.\u000a\u000aLobbyists for the glass-and-steel German city point to the presence of the German and European central banks, an English-speaking regulator and almost a dozen new high-rise buildings as big draws for finance firms seeking a foothold on the Continent.\u000a\u000aWhile the case looks strong, Paris boosters argue that it has also got plenty of holes. Most banks that have promised to move to Frankfurt, they point out, only talk of establishing legal headquarters there, which can be accomplished with minimum staff. That\u2019s not the same as shifting an entire trading room.\u000a\u000aMajor post-Brexit decisions on moving operations are still to come, with estimates of how many jobs will be affected ranging from 30,000 to 230,000 depending on the outcome of negotiations between the U.K. and EU. When banks do shift greater resources, particularly for their trading operations, Paris advocates argue they will pay attention to surrounding financial conditions \u2014 and balk at concerns about the German banking sector.\u000a\u000aThen there is the relative size and prestige of Paris versus Frankfurt. The former has a population of 10 million and the economy of a global metropolis on par with London and New York, while the latter is an up-and-coming seat for central banks with a population of 730,000.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe\u2019re getting a rather distorted image of Frankfurt as the hands-down winner of this race for Brexit jobs\u201d \u2014 Arnaud de Bresson, managing director of Paris Europlace\u000a\u000aGermany may have more attractive tax and labor conditions, but France\u2019s new president, Emmanuel Macron, is charging ahead with plans to make France competitive. He plans to scrap the highest bracket of payroll tax for banks and other firms that don\u2019t pay VAT and to cancel a planned extension of tax on share trading. Macron has also pledged to make sure bonuses are not taken into account when labor courts decide on unfair dismissal compensation.\u000a\u000aThe rub: Don\u2019t count Paris out.\u000a\u000a\u201cAt the moment we\u2019re getting a rather distorted image of Frankfurt as the hands-down winner of this race for Brexit jobs,\u201d said Arnaud de Bresson, managing director of Paris Europlace, an organization that promotes the city as a financial center.\u000a\u000a\u201cBut when we start talking about relocating entire trading teams, about big-time staffing decisions, Paris is still very much a contender \u2026 We\u2019re convinced that in the short to medium term, Paris\u2019 advantages will start to shine through in a compelling way, especially compared to Frankfurt,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aFrankfurt\u2019s Achilles\u2019 heel\u000a\u000aFrankfurt\u2019s strengths on paper have allowed the German city to pull ahead of its French rival in winning commitments to move there from big banks. Its official bid to host the European Banking Authority \u2014 the EU\u2019s banking regulator \u2014 submitted Monday placed great emphasis on the city\u2019s dominance in financial market supervision as well as its growing clientele of banks.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhen it comes to customer business, Frankfurt is where the clients are,\u201d Michael Horn, a spokesperson for the Hessian minister for European and federal affairs, said in July.\u000a\u000aU.S. bank Citigroup, Britain\u2019s Standard Chartered and Japan\u2019s Nomura are among those that have decided to make Frankfurt their legal base.\u000a\u000aBut Bresson says the devil is in the word \u201clegal.\u201d Many such decisions, he said, may boil down to opening a beachhead office with a handful of staffers in order to have a presence on the Continent, not a bona fide trading hub.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhere your legal entity is based is not where your people are based,\u201d JPMorgan Chief Executive Jamie Dimon said in July at a conference in Paris. \u201cThe people could be in Paris, in the Netherlands, or Madrid or anywhere in the EU. We haven\u2019t decided yet.\u201d\u000a\u000aAmong banks committed to Frankfurt, Citibank is relocating an estimated 200 staff. By contrast, HSBC said in January it would move 1,000 trading staff to Paris. Added to commitments to repatriate staff from a slew of French banks including Société Générale and Crédit Agricole, Paris appears only slightly behind Frankfurt on Brexit job moves already announced: The former has clocked 2,500 to the latter\u2019s 2,800, according to calculations by Paris Europlace.\u000a\u000aAnother 30 financial institutions, including large Asian and U.S. banks, are in talks with French regulators about moving to Paris, according to Europlace.\u000a\u000aOverall, the Bruegel think tank estimates some 30,000 jobs could move to the Continent from the City of London if Brexit becomes a reality, while others put the figure much higher. That means that the process is only beginning. When big decisions come, banks will look at a range of factors, notably the health of a country\u2019s banking sector.\u000a\u000aHere, France has the upper hand, Bresson said. \u201cCommerzbank is in a delicate situation, Deutsche Bank has difficulties internationally, and then there are the Landesbanks, which also have issues,\u201d he said. \u201cThis shows there are difficulties within the system, which could create problems down the line for interbank lending for financial firms.\u201d\u000a\u000aFrench banks, four of which are in the European top 10 for size, are not a persistent worry for regulators. Intensive trading activities mean there is deep expertise among regulators. And contrary to some claims from rivals, they are briefing potential clients in English.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe big difference between Paris and Frankfurt in regulation is that Paris has greater expertise in terms of market activity than the German authority,\u201d Bresson said.\u000a\u000aFrance changing\u000a\u000aFor now, Germany has a lower corporate tax rate than France (29.7 percent versus 33.3 percent). But the French rate is set to fall to 28 percent by 2020. On July 7, Prime Minister Edouard Philippe rolled out a series of other measures aimed at Brexiting banks, including scrapping the top bracket of payroll tax for financial sectors workers.\u000a\u000a\u201cOnly Paris and its La Défense neighborhood can propose a viable alternative to companies installed in London\u201d \u2014 Marie Celie Guillaume, chief of Defacto\u000a\u000aRigid labor rules have long been a concern for foreign banks considering doing business in France, an issue HSBC\u2019s chief executive, Stuart Gulliver, underscored in July. Planned reforms were \u201cvery positive\u201d but banks wanted to see whether Macron would be able to carry out his agenda and whether he will be able to defend it during a second term, Gulliver said.\u000a\u000aYet Macron is charging ahead with changes to the labor code, with a series of executive decrees due to be published no later than the end of September, according to Philippe. The president, a former Rothschild banker himself, is bent on making France a winner from Brexit and is throwing his weight behind efforts to draw bankers to Paris.\u000a\u000aOne of the main draws of Paris is that it is a more attractive place to live, with a culinary and cultural scene to rival London\u2019s and satisfy large-walleted finance employees. The city also has plenty of space to welcome an influx of bankers, with seven new skyscrapers due to be built in the La Défense Business district by 2021, amounting to 375,000 square meters of new office space.\u000a\u000a\u201cOnly Paris and its La Défense neighborhood can propose a viable alternative to companies installed in London, either in terms of economic environment or lifestyle for the workers,\u201d said Marie Celie Guillaume, chief of Defacto, the company that promotes La Défense.
