aVEU Commissioner Gunther Oettinger says the U.K. must continue to meets its financial obligations to the EU even after leaving the bloc | Emmanuel Dunand/AFP via Getty Images Günther Oettinger: UK must pay EU until 2020 despite Brexit \u2018Very unlikely\u2019 EU will hand over remainder of promised \u20ac4.3B in aid to Turkey by 2020, commissioner for budget also said.\u000a\u000aBritain will have to continue paying the European Union until 2020 even if it leaves the bloc in 2019, the EU\u2019s budget commissioner reiterated in an interview published Monday in German paper Bild.\u000a\u000aGünther Oettinger, the European commissioner for budget and human resources, said the U.K. must honor its obligations to fund long-term projects.\u000a\u000a\u201cLondon will have to transfer funds to Brussels at least until 2020,\u201d said Oettinger.\u000a\u000aOettinger said Germany would likely face \u201cmanageable\u201d additional payments in the single-digit billion-euro range to make up for the EU budget black hole left by Britain\u2019s departure from the bloc.\u000a\u000aOettinger\u2019s comments came as the Telegraph reported the U.K. was willing to pay a \u20ac40 billion Brexit divorce bill. Downing Street denied the reports.\u000a\u000aThe budget commissioner also told Bild it was \u201cvery unlikely\u201d the EU would hand over the remainder of a promised \u20ac4.3 billion of EU pre-accession aid to Turkey by the end of 2020.\u000a\u000aThe funds were supposed to \u201cpromote projects that bring Turkey closer to Europe, for example through the training of judges, prosecutors or journalists,\u201d Oettinger said. \u201cAgainst the backdrop of the political development in Turkey, I cannot imagine such projects will continue to be promoted.\u201d\u000a\u000aOettinger also discussed the ongoing Dieselgate scandal in Germany. \u201cThe results of the diesel summit must now be implemented quickly,\u201d said the commissioner, referring to last week\u2019s meeting in which Germany\u2019s auto giants pledged to cut harmful emissions by fitting cars with software upgrades.\u000a\u000aIf it isn\u2019t clear within \u201ca few months at the latest\u201d whether the agreed measures are sufficient, carmakers must, if necessary, also refit vehicles with technical modifications to avoid bans, he said. But the commissioner defended diesel fuel.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe must not demonize diesel. It is significantly more efficient than a gasoline engine, and it also ejects less carbon dioxide,\u201d Oettinger noted.
