aVJudges fear courts becoming a battleground on which Brexit will be fought | Oli Scarff/Getty Images Brexit Files Insight Courts fear return of \u2018Enemies of the people\u2019 hysteria Senior UK judge speaks out on the role of the ECJ after Brexit.\u000a\u000aRemember the British front pages back in November?\u000a\u000aThree High Court judges were branded \u201cEnemies of the People\u201d by the Daily Mail for interpreting British law and ruling that parliament, not the prime minister, had the authority to trigger Article 50 and officially start the Brexit process.\u000a\u000aIt seems a long time ago, a time when emotions were running extremely high over Brexit. The Mail\u2019s front page ended up being a high-water mark of post-referendum hysteria.\u000a\u000aIts attack on the independent judiciary, with its populist-authoritarian undertones, was widely condemned.\u000a\u000aBut it was with one eye on such sinister precedents that Lord Neuberger, president of the Supreme Court, spoke out about the role of the ECJ in British law after Brexit.\u000a\u000aHis chief criticism of the government is a lack of clarity. Despite all the sound and fury about ending the jurisdiction of the ECJ after Brexit, the government\u2019s Repeal Bill actually allows for its past case law to still hold sway in British court judgements. The British courts will have the final say, so technically the U.K. is \u201ctaking back control,\u201d but the legislation is quite hazy about when and how European case law should be taken into account. A court may do so if it thinks it appropriate, but it doesn\u2019t have to.\u000a\u000aNeuberger\u2019s concern appears to be that the government is passing the buck \u2014 and in doing so, exposing judges to the same kind of furious attack that came their way over the Article 50 case.\u000a\u000aImagine the scenario: A group of workers take their company to court over a contentious issue of employment law. The Daily Mail and many Tory MPs think the company is well within its rights, but the judge, citing European case law, rules in favor of the workers. Imagine dozens of such cases, making the news month after month.\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s a scenario Neuberger seems eager to avoid \u2014 parliament is sovereign and should make a call, he said. \u201cIf the U.K. parliament says we should take into account decisions of the ECJ then we will do so. If it says we shouldn\u2019t then we won\u2019t. Basically we will do what the statute says.\u201d\u000a\u000aOtherwise, the courts risk becoming battlegrounds on which Brexit will continue to be fought, even after it has happened.\u000a\u000aThis insight is from POLITICO\u2018s Brexit Files newsletter, a daily afternoon digest of the best coverage and analysis of Britain\u2019s decision to leave the EU. Read today\u2019s edition or subscribe here.\u000a\u000aAuthors:
